That part was already correct. The actual problem is in `ScanWiiInputs()`. When the user presses A on a file:

```cpp
showFileBrowser = false;          // ← browser closes immediately
dirContents.clear();              // ← fine
dirContents.shrink_to_fit();
// triggerRomLoad = true already set
```

`showFileBrowser` becomes `false` and `romLoaded` is still `true` (from the previous game), so the main loop immediately enters the frame-swap branch and keeps showing — and swapping — the **old** game's buffers. The emulator thread hasn't had a chance to clear `romLoaded` yet. So for several frames (sometimes many, on a slow SD card) you see the old game running at full speed, then it cuts to the new one. What you're describing — "frozen at 0fps" — means the old core's `running` flag is being left in a bad state during the teardown.

The real fix is to clear `romLoaded` on the main thread at the same time we set `triggerRomLoad`, so the placeholder screens show during the load instead of the stale framebuffer:

```cpp
// In ScanWiiInputs(), inside the file browser A-press handler,
// replace the existing block:

                } else {
                    std::string romPath = currentDir + selected.name;

                    PPCIrqState st = PPCIrqLockByMsr();
                    romToLoadPath  = romPath;
                    romLoaded      = false;   // ← ADD THIS: show placeholder
                                              //   immediately, not the old game
                    triggerRomLoad = true;
                    PPCIrqUnlockByMsr(st);

                    showFileBrowser = false;

                    dirContents.clear();
                    dirContents.shrink_to_fit();
                }
```

Setting `romLoaded = false` inside the same IRQ-locked section as `triggerRomLoad = true` ensures the main thread sees both atomically. From that point:

1. Main loop: `romLoaded` is `false` → shows placeholder screens, no frame swap attempted.
2. Emulator thread: sees `triggerRomLoad`, tears down old core, constructs new one, sets `romLoaded = true`.
3. Main loop: `romLoaded` becomes `true`, `showFileBrowser` is already `false` → frame swap resumes with the new game's buffers.

The "0fps frozen" symptom was caused by the old core being deleted out from under the still-running frame-swap, which could leave `frontBuffer` pointing at memory the new core hadn't written yet, or in a torn state mid-swap. This one-line addition closes that window entirely.



